{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"xVLAMOTRzWfRVwfsVMq6f","title":"Lecture 10","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"type":"note","desc":"","links":[],"anchors":{"temperature-sensor":{"type":"header","text":"Temperature Sensor","value":"temperature-sensor","line":9,"column":0},"resistance-temperature-detectors-rtd":{"type":"header","text":"Resistance Temperature Detectors (RTD)","value":"resistance-temperature-detectors-rtd","line":11,"column":0},"thermocouples":{"type":"header","text":"Thermocouples","value":"thermocouples","line":24,"column":0}},"fname":"courses.Semester 5.Sensors.Lecture 10","updated":1633600658724,"created":1633599517028,"parent":"BU8smu6Xa4e3tkB0iVHT9","children":[],"data":{},"contentHash":"e1ffb3d9b89745b78dd7ee04873b7e47","custom":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"lecture-10\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#lecture-10\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Lecture 10</h1>\n<h2 id=\"temperature-sensor\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#temperature-sensor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Temperature Sensor</h2>\n<h2 id=\"resistance-temperature-detectors-rtd\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#resistance-temperature-detectors-rtd\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Resistance Temperature Detectors (RTD)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-11-54.png\"></li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-17-18.png\"></li>\n<li>Typical value of R0 is 100 ohms and that of alpha will depend on the material and geometry of the setting.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-18-13.png\"></li>\n<li>Usually in real world, the RTD is placed in the heated chamber and you will be located far away. This means that the wires would have some resistance.</li>\n<li>Therefore, the voltage you get is actually the potential drop from RTD and the wires.</li>\n<li>This might lead to large errors.</li>\n<li>4 Wire RTD measurement\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-20-41.png\"></li>\n<li>The drop in the inner wires can be neglected because the volmeter has high resistance and hence calibration will remain valid.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"thermocouples\"><a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading\" href=\"#thermocouples\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\"><use xlink:href=\"#svg-link\"></use></svg></a>Thermocouples</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-23-07.png\"></li>\n<li>Cold junction compensation\n<ul>\n<li>Copper wire will have some resitance and thermocouple materials used.</li>\n<li>Thus, cold junction will also have different voltage than hot end.</li>\n<li>Hence, we need to compensate.</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-28-56.png\"></li>\n<li>Automatic Junction Compensation\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-31-44.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Merits and Demerits\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-25-34.png\"></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><img src=\"/notes/assets/images/2021-10-07-15-26-41.png\"> </li>\n</ul>","noteIndex":{"id":"PAQSbL1rYQAohZXoEr47M","title":"Curated Notes","vault":{"fsPath":"vault"},"type":"note","desc":"","links":[],"anchors":{},"fname":"root","updated":1630150480330,"created":1629975412335,"parent":null,"children":["Jq5ki9jf1QLTdc3DYLRW4","3ONxZ3Khb7nFPdLxlV1ib"],"data":{},"contentHash":"250e1442f895f06dba982d3a97cc447f","custom":{"nav_order":0,"permalink":"/"},"body":"\n\r\n\r\nYou have reached the home page of my curated notes. I am a third year student pursuing Computer Science and Engineering at Ahmedabad University.\r\n\r\nFeel free to use this resource to its best potential and reach out to me on [Linkedin](https://www.linkedin.com/in/sameep-vani/) and do checkout my [GitHub](https://